close_symbols: any side-effect behavior / contracts for the above init functions (docs or implementations)
platform/test stubs invoked by init functions (e.g. UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr)
explanation:
To determine whether any statements in OS_API_Init constitute dead code (i.e., their removal would not change program behaviour) the analyser must know all symbols that affect control flow, observable side-effects, and behaviour mutations performed by the function. Specifically:

- OS_SharedGlobalVars and its fields (GlobalState, MicroSecPerTick, TicksPerSecond, DebugLevel): the function reads, zeroes and writes this global state; these fields drive early-return, later checks, and warnings. Their definitions and sizes are required to know whether these operations have observable effects.

- OS_INIT_MAGIC_NUMBER and OS_SHUTDOWN_MAGIC_NUMBER: these constants determine the initial early-return and the shutdown-state assignment; needed to check if the early-return path is ever possible or redundant.

- OS_SUCCESS and OS_ERROR: return-code semantics are used throughout to gate subsequent calls; removal of calls that only run when return_code==OS_SUCCESS could be dead if return_code never permits them — so the values/semantics are required.

- osal_objtype_t and OS_OBJECT_TYPE_USER (and the OS_OBJECT_TYPE_* values used in the switch): the loop bounds and switch cases depend on the object-type enumeration; to decide whether particular case blocks execute (and so whether their bodies are dead) the enum definitions and range are needed.

- OS_DEBUG and OSAL_CONFIG_DEBUG_PRINTF: debug logging calls are observable behaviour in many builds. Whether OS_DEBUG produces side effects (or compiles to nothing) depends on these macros; removal of logging could or could not be considered dead depending on that.

- memset and sizeof(OS_SharedGlobalVars): zeroing the global struct is an operation with observable effect; knowledge of the actual size and whether memset has any platform-specific semantics is needed.

- OS_ObjectIdInit and OS_API_Impl_Init and all per-type API init functions (Task/Queue/BinSem/CountSem/Mutex/Module/TimeBase/TimerCb/File/Dir/FileSys/Console/CondVar) and Network/Socket inits: these functions are called for initialization and may perform crucial side-effects (resource allocation, register handlers, set timing globals, create tasks, etc.). To decide whether any of the calls (or the surrounding conditional logic) are dead, the analyser must know the side-effect contracts or implementations of these functions (including whether they modify OS_SharedGlobalVars fields or global state, whether they are no-ops on certain platforms, whether they are required for correct behaviour, or whether they are never reachable due to loop bounds/return codes).

- Any test-platform stubs or instrumentation functions referenced transitively by the init functions (e.g. UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr): these can change behaviour (simulate failures, short-circuit initialization) in test builds, affecting whether branches in OS_API_Init are ever taken; include them so test-time behaviour is accounted for.

Collecting the above symbols (declarations, macro definitions and the implementations or documented side-effect contracts of the called init functions) allows an analyser to determine which operations in OS_API_Init are actually required for correct observable behaviour and which — if any — would be removable without changing program behaviour (i.e. dead code under MISRA definition).
